00:27:27.020 --> 00:27:30.300
But if you look at the other performance characteristics, it's really not that good

486
00:27:30.340 --> 00:27:32.760
of an assay, and precision-recall here is poor.

487
00:27:34.200 --> 00:27:37.600
So for the non-data scientists, this is probably going to be

488
00:27:37.700 --> 00:27:38.300
interesting.

489
00:27:40.560 --> 00:27:43.909
Does anyone know what-- The non-data scientists know what

490
00:27:43.960 --> 00:27:46.580
precision-recall is? It sounds very fancy.

491
00:27:47.240 --> 00:27:51.020
So precision actually, for the clinicians out there, is positive predictive

492
00:27:51.080 --> 00:27:54.660
value, renamed as precision. So data scientists know it as precision.

493
00:27:54.780 --> 00:27:56.900
We know it as positive predictive value.

494
00:27:56.920 --> 00:28:00.000
And I think translating between our two worlds is important.

495
00:28:00.390 --> 00:28:02.300
And then recall is sensitivity.

496
00:28:03.340 --> 00:28:07.320
So all I'm telling you, which the clinical lab people in the audience

497
00:28:07.340 --> 00:28:10.930
know, is you can't just judge a test based on sensitivity and

498
00:28:10.960 --> 00:28:14.900
specificity. You actually have to know positive predictive value, negative

499
00:28:14.960 --> 00:28:17.280
predictive value, reproducibility.

500
00:28:17.310 --> 00:28:20.980
And so I'm holding the bar high for the data scientists in the

501
00:28:21.020 --> 00:28:21.420
audience

502
00:28:22.340 --> 00:28:26.080
that your papers have to include things like AUPRC as well as

503
00:28:26.300 --> 00:28:29.440
AUROC and think about other aspects of it.

504
00:28:32.060 --> 00:28:34.020
Maybe one second on positive predictive value.

505
00:28:34.520 --> 00:28:38.200
As you tune your assay and the cutoffs of your assay to capture more

506
00:28:38.240 --> 00:28:41.900
patients, that is to have a higher sensitivity because you want to

507
00:28:41.940 --> 00:28:43.520
screen for patients and find all of them.

508
00:28:44.240 --> 00:28:45.460
As you make that cutoff

509
00:28:46.460 --> 00:28:50.120
more loose, that you get more patients, the chance of any

510
00:28:50.219 --> 00:28:52.400
positive being true positive begins to fall.

511
00:28:52.460 --> 00:28:55.900
So you begin to have this inverse relationship with positive predictive value.

512
00:28:56.320 --> 00:28:59.580
And as I said in the beginning, clinicians don't like when you have false

513
00:28:59.640 --> 00:29:03.140
positives. If you tell them that the patient has an EGFR mutation, and they don't,

514
00:29:03.220 --> 00:29:05.940
they get very upset with pathology, like really upset,

515
00:29:07.120 --> 00:29:07.720
as do patients.

516
00:29:08.760 --> 00:29:10.100
Coming back to explainability.

517
00:29:12.700 --> 00:29:16.480
The data scientists in the audience probably do know this, but many

518
00:29:16.880 --> 00:29:20.400
of you won't. I really like this example for explainability.

519
00:29:20.620 --> 00:29:24.160
It's an example of four distributions of data, 11 data points on an

520
00:29:24.340 --> 00:29:25.560
XY coordinate.

521
00:29:26.750 --> 00:29:30.580
And what's interesting about these 11 points is to a

522
00:29:30.620 --> 00:29:33.620
human who looks at them, they're very different data sets.

523
00:29:33.680 --> 00:29:36.720
No one would think immediately that these are related at all.

524
00:29:37.520 --> 00:29:41.320
However, statistically, if you asked a machine, are they related,

525
00:29:41.740 --> 00:29:45.700
the machine would tell you their X coordinates, mean, and variance, their Y

526
00:29:45.780 --> 00:29:49.359
coordinates, mean, and variance, and their regression lines are exactly the same.

527
00:29:51.080 --> 00:29:53.220
Right? That kind of blew my mind the first time I saw this.

528
00:29:53.260 --> 00:29:57.040
And so to expect a machine to understand what things look like based

529
00:29:57.100 --> 00:30:00.960
on statistical embeddings is just something I think we all

530
00:30:01.060 --> 00:30:05.040
have to be aware of. And as pathologists, I like to go back and look

531
00:30:05.080 --> 00:30:08.580
at things. And so at least for the next few years, I think we're going to have to

532
00:30:08.600 --> 00:30:12.520
work very closely together, that is data scientists and pathologists, to

533
00:30:12.560 --> 00:30:16.430
work through where we might have confounders and things like this.

534
00:30:17.440 --> 00:30:19.880
This is one of very interesting examples

535
00:30:21.120 --> 00:30:24.690
that I've seen, which is a really interesting paper from 2018, which showed

536
00:30:24.960 --> 00:30:28.580
taking pictures of skin lesions, whether they're melanoma or not.

537
00:30:29.220 --> 00:30:30.000
And

538
00:30:31.400 --> 00:30:35.260
what was confounding in this study was the patients who had malignant melanoma had

539
00:30:35.300 --> 00:30:39.004
a rulerNext to their melanomas on their skin.

540
00:30:39.764 --> 00:30:43.404
And the machine learned if there was a ruler next to the skin

541
00:30:43.464 --> 00:30:45.224
lesion that they had melanoma.

542
00:30:46.954 --> 00:30:50.304
And it makes sense. Why wouldn't a machine-- that's the shortest cut, probably the

543
00:30:50.404 --> 00:30:54.344
most accurate way to detect a melanoma.

544
00:30:54.424 --> 00:30:54.804
But it's,

545
00:30:56.064 --> 00:30:59.284
I don't know. There's these blatant examples that you can see for pathologists

546
00:30:59.324 --> 00:31:03.304
circling. Did you circle or an arrow on a slide? Those kind of things.

547
00:31:05.444 --> 00:31:06.144
Coming back to

548
00:31:08.024 --> 00:31:11.844
my post-doc's ability to build an ALK predictor, he pulled out

549
00:31:11.904 --> 00:31:14.904
using one of these unsupervised explainability

550
00:31:14.944 --> 00:31:16.654
tools. What were the

551
00:31:18.304 --> 00:31:20.193
patches that drove the prediction?

552
00:31:20.684 --> 00:31:21.244
On the right,

553
00:31:22.884 --> 00:31:25.434
for the pathologists, hopefully, you recognize there's a lot of signet ring cells,

554
00:31:25.444 --> 00:31:27.364
and that was good because that's really something we see in

555
00:31:28.224 --> 00:31:32.044
ALK-positive slides. These are all fluids, by the way.

556
00:31:32.464 --> 00:31:35.123
So we see that we had a lot of fluids in our data set.

557
00:31:35.144 --> 00:31:37.444
But on the left, the

558
00:31:38.704 --> 00:31:40.983
patches on the left were also driving this predictor.

