00:31:46.144 --> 00:31:49.824
is nothing useful in any of those slides, in any of those patches.

561
00:31:49.864 --> 00:31:52.804
What you see are fragments of bone, a lot of blood,

562
00:31:53.984 --> 00:31:54.784
sometimes nothing.

563
00:31:55.784 --> 00:31:59.644
And so what is that? I think this is coming back to, if you remember the predictor

564
00:31:59.724 --> 00:32:02.224
I had in our old heuristic model,

565
00:32:03.184 --> 00:32:06.524
is these are what you would see in a needle

566
00:32:06.604 --> 00:32:10.344
biopsy of a metastatic lesion. We often see these

567
00:32:10.404 --> 00:32:13.094
poor, small, fragmented, bloody samples.

568
00:32:13.604 --> 00:32:17.104
And so, yes, it's actually contributing to the ALK-positive calls.

569
00:32:19.704 --> 00:32:22.124
What other issues are there in building these models?

570
00:32:25.224 --> 00:32:26.344
Let me do a time check quickly.

571
00:32:28.424 --> 00:32:29.364
Oh, we still have time. Okay.

572
00:32:31.564 --> 00:32:32.044
Talk too much.

573
00:32:33.264 --> 00:32:34.924
Can I take a drink? Do you mind? Give me one second.

574
00:32:45.764 --> 00:32:49.364
Besides confounding bad, horrible pathology slides,

575
00:32:49.684 --> 00:32:51.824
what else can confound the development of

576
00:32:53.044 --> 00:32:56.964
these models? Well, we have entities in pathology and medicine that

577
00:32:57.004 --> 00:33:00.903
are super rare, that are probably never represented in the foundation model

578
00:33:00.984 --> 00:33:04.744
slides. Despite there being 100,000 or a million slides,

579
00:33:05.464 --> 00:33:06.664
each with a billion pixels,

580
00:33:07.664 --> 00:33:11.364
they didn't have all of them. And so I'm just showing you one disease, which is

581
00:33:11.384 --> 00:33:13.684
bone and soft tissue sarcomas,

582
00:33:14.764 --> 00:33:15.164
for which

583
00:33:16.364 --> 00:33:18.764
there's what we call a long tail of rare entities.

584
00:33:19.044 --> 00:33:22.884
This is the current WHO. There's 170 recognized soft tissue

585
00:33:22.944 --> 00:33:26.174
tumors. Do you think all of them are represented sufficiently to build a foundation

586
00:33:26.244 --> 00:33:28.964
model that fully embeds all of the unique features?

587
00:33:30.044 --> 00:33:31.403
And even though there are 170

588
00:33:32.364 --> 00:33:36.274
different chapters in this book, I guarantee you each one of those

589
00:33:36.364 --> 00:33:39.933
has 10 unique histologic subtypes or

590
00:33:40.264 --> 00:33:41.373
slightly different features.

591
00:33:42.224 --> 00:33:45.864
So we just don't have enough of these rare entities to replace the

592
00:33:45.884 --> 00:33:46.624
pathologist.

593
00:33:47.844 --> 00:33:51.764
The problem can be approached by this, quote, "zero-shot

594
00:33:51.824 --> 00:33:54.904
methods that incorporate vision language," and

595
00:33:54.944 --> 00:33:58.904
Faisal's CONCH model did that. So it was trained not just on images, but

596
00:33:58.964 --> 00:34:02.704
also on language. So presumably, the WHO textbook was

597
00:34:02.724 --> 00:34:06.414
taken in by his model, and so maybe it could just read the chapter and

598
00:34:07.684 --> 00:34:11.464
fill in the missing morphologic information in his model. So that's possible.

599
00:34:12.444 --> 00:34:16.265
But I think larger dedicated training sets from cooperative efforts and federated

600
00:34:16.304 --> 00:34:19.265
learning is going to be required, and I think that's something AACR, for

601
00:34:19.324 --> 00:34:23.265
instance, can be involved with. And some of us have talked about how to

602
00:34:23.705 --> 00:34:26.403
begin to build these kind of federated models.

603
00:34:27.364 --> 00:34:29.584
I showed you a few examples where AI doesn't have to be perfect.

604
00:34:29.784 --> 00:34:32.844
I'm asking you to be perfect on some things, but AI doesn't have to be perfect on

605
00:34:32.924 --> 00:34:33.344
everything.

